04884nam a22007815i 9780804798600DE-B159720200723103303.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200723t20202016cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2015030663  a97808047986007 a10.1515/97808047986002doi  a(DE-B1597)563662  a(OCoLC)1178769148  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aLC3736.D4bJ34 2016 4aLC3736.D4bJ34 2016eb 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a371.829088/297094892231 aJaffe-Walter, Reva, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCoercive Concern :bNationalism, Liberalism, and the Schooling of Muslim Youth /cReva Jaffe-Walter. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aAnthropology of Policy00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Ethnographic Journeys through Concern -- tChapter 1. Imagining the Nation -- tChapter 2. Integration and Immigration -- tChapter 3. Liberalizing Muslim Girls -- tChapter 4. Negotiating Relationships to Hostlands and Homelands -- tChapter 5. Somali by Nature, Muslim by Choice, Danish by Paper -- tChapter 6. Teachers' Counter-Narratives and Comparative Sites of Possibility -- tConclusion. Interrogating Liberal Blind Spots and Silences -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMany liberal-minded Western democracies pride themselves on their commitments to egalitarianism, the fair treatment of immigrants, and the right to education. These environments would seem to provide a best-case scenario for the reception of immigrant youth. But that is not always the case. Coercive Concern explores how stereotypes of Muslim immigrants in Western liberal societies flow through public schools into everyday interactions, informing how Muslim youth are perceived by teachers and peers. Beyond simply identifying the presence of racialized speech in schools, this book uncovers how coercive assimilation is cloaked in benevolent narratives of care and concern. Coercive Concern provides an ethnographic critique of the "concern" that animates integration policy in Danish schools. Reva Jaffe-Walter focuses on the experiences of Muslim youth at a public school where over 40% of the student body is of immigrant descent, showing how schools operate as sites of governance. These efforts are led by political leaders who promote national fears of immigrant take-over, by teachers in schools, and by everyday citizens who are concerned about "problems" of immigration. Jaffe-Walter exposes the psychic and material costs immigrant youth endure when living in the shadow of social scrutiny, but she also charts a path forward by uncovering the resources these youth need to attain social mobility and success.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aChildren of immigrantsxEducationxDenmark. 0aChildren of immigrantsxEducationzDenmark. 0aImmigrant youthxEducationxDenmark. 0aImmigrant youthxEducationzDenmark. 0aLiberalismxDenmarkxDenmark. 0aLiberalismzDenmark. 0aMuslim youthxEducationxDenmark. 0aMuslim youthxEducationzDenmark. 0aMuslimsxCultural assimilationxDenmark. 0aMuslimsxCultural assimilationzDenmark. 0aNationalismxDenmark. 0aNationalismzDenmark. 4aIslamophobia. 4aMuslim youth. 4aassimilation. 4aconcern. 4aeducation. 4aimmigrant students. 4aliberalism. 4anationalism. 4aracialization. 4astereotyping. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311070397940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080479860040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804798600423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter